{
  "doc_id": "56473",
  "text": "Collectively, the analysis of phase II immunotherapy studies with autologous NK cells failed to show efficacy [CITATION_1] . Several factors may have accounted for the disappointing results, including competition with the recipient's lymphocytes for cytokines and \"space\"; inhibition of autologous NK cells by self-MHC [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] ; chronic immunosuppression induced by the tumor on host immunity; and expansion of Treg cells by IL-2 (127). Autologous NK cells are currently being tested in patients with hematological malignancies and solid tumors (NCT00720785; Table 2) (142). In this trial, which is recruiting participants, patients will receive immune suppressive therapy with pentostatin, followed by bortezomib to sensitize tumor cells to NK cytotoxicity [CITATION_5] , escalating doses of autologous NK cells and IL-2.",
